-- Regression: emit_c.c HEAP_ALLOC malloc without NULL check (FIX-01 rank 3).
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 65 CORRECTNESS-AUDIT.md §3 row 3 and §6 row
-- 1 flagged src/lir/emit_c.c:3159-3168 (the IRON_LIR_HEAP_ALLOC codegen case)
-- as a bare malloc followed by an unguarded dereference. Every Iron program
-- that used the `heap` keyword had ironc emit:
--     Iron_Data *_v3 = (Iron_Data *)malloc(sizeof(Iron_Data));
--     *_v3 = some_value;   // NULL deref on OOM — silent SIGSEGV
-- Users under memory pressure got a generic segfault with no way to tell
-- "out of memory" apart from "wild pointer bug in my code". The bug affected
-- the most frequently emitted allocation path in the compiler — every
-- heap-allocated object construction.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Pre-fix (emit_c.c:3159 case body):
--     %s *_vN = (%s *)malloc(sizeof(%s));    <- line 3168
--     *_vN    = inner_val;                    <- line 3175, may deref NULL
--
-- Post-fix:
--     %s *_vN = (%s *)malloc(sizeof(%s));
--     if (!_vN) iron_oom_abort("emit_c HEAP_ALLOC");
--     *_vN    = inner_val;
--
-- The guard routes OOM through iron_oom_abort (declared in
-- src/diagnostics/diagnostics.h, defined in src/runtime/iron_oom.c, added by
-- 67-02 Task 1) which prints "iron: out of memory at emit_c HEAP_ALLOC" to
-- stderr and calls abort(3). Every compiled Iron binary links iron_oom_abort
-- transitively via iron_runtime.h's diagnostics.h include.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** src/lir/emit_c.c IRON_LIR_HEAP_ALLOC case rewritten to
-- emit a 3-line `if (!_vN) iron_oom_abort(...);` guard between the malloc
-- call and the `*_vN =` dereference. Covers FIX-01 rank 3 from the Phase 65
-- audit. Phase 67-02 Task 3. This fixture verifies the guard is present in
-- the generated C and that a normal non-OOM `heap Point(3, 4)` still
-- compiles and runs correctly.
--
-- **Severity.** H — pre-fix every Iron program using `heap` was one OOM
-- away from a silent segfault with no diagnostic; post-fix users get a
-- clear "iron: out of memory at emit_c HEAP_ALLOC" message before abort.

object Point {
  var x: Int
  var y: Int
    init(x: Int, y: Int) {
        self.x = x
        self.y = y
    }
}

func main() {
  val p = heap Point(3, 4)
  println("point.x: {p.x}")
  println("point.y: {p.y}")
}
